<font color="#FF0000">MY BROTHERS ARE HEAVY</font><br>
<tt>Fri Jul 25 18:27:25 US/Eastern 1997
</tt><p>
Tom - Cook - Arthur:  Do you remember having a feeling that you just couldn't stand to lose anymore of what you had left?  I recall a time when I didn't want to lose any more friends... So! I quit making friends (mostly on my second tour.) Today, I only have a few that I trust.  I prefer to be alone or at least I think I feel that way.  Sometimes, I get very lonely.<br>
When Bro Cook writes, an overwhelming love for my KIA buddies returns to knock me in the dirt.  Names, faces, and voices return... numbing doesn't work anymore.  I compress a lot of thought into poetry.  <br><br>
&quot;He's Not My Friend!&quot;<br><br>
Who is this person sprawled at my feet<br>
with shrapnel all in his chest?<br>
He wasn't my friend in his short time here,<br>
even though he tried his best.<br><br>
It is better that he died as a stranger<br>
than to have died among his friends.<br>
He has left no one here to suffer<br>
in this horror that never ends.<br><br>
So, I will roll him up in a poncho<br>
and shoo away the flies.<br>
Then I will greet his nameless replacement<br>
with silence and cold-stoney eyes.<br><br>
They continue to join our ranks<br>
in never ending streams.<br>
To err, then fall and thrash about,<br>
emitting their pitiful screams.<br><br>
Why should I die with all who fall,<br>
who take so much in their leaving?<br>
Besides, I have no need for friends anymore<br>
and I'm not worth a damn at grieving.<br><br>
From &quot;Scars and Stripes, Forever&quot; Copyright 1990 Edward Ramon<br><br>
I suppose the extreme is to try and love every vet and rescue everyone.  It is all or none.  A tough way to live.<br>
I hate to lean on you guys, but have you ever felt this.<br><br>
&quot;Being There&quot;<br><br>
We sat apart in the smoke filled room<br>
and I read his troubled mind.<br>
I heard the pealing bells of doom<br>
and feared what I would find.<br><br>
His heart was broken and bleeding,<br>
his soul was stripped and raw.<br>
I felt him softly pleading,<br>
I heard everything I saw.<br><br>
The raced began, to find despair,<br>
but I matched him stride for stride.<br>
It troubled him to see me there,<br>
then he opened up inside.<br><br>
&quot;I can't forget their mocking curse,<br>
spewn forth on fetid breath.<br>
Surviving a war is surely worse<br>
than dying an honorable death.&quot;<br><br>
I heard him think, &quot;Sweet darkness<br>
hide me from scornful eyes.<br>
Seal my ears with deafness<br>
and hush the scalding lies.<br><br>
Send the rain to drench my face<br>
and mask these falling tears.<br>
I have know enough disgrace <br>
to last a thousand years.&quot;<br><br>
&quot;Give me back my numbness.<br>
I have nothing left to share.<br>
Bury me in knowing quietnes.<br>
Stay out of my vacant stare.<br><br>
Just lay me down when I am done<br>
beneath rows of clean white crosses.<br>
God still knows who really won<br>
and who should share the losses.&quot;<br><br>
I rode with him to the very brink<br>
and felt all that he had to say.<br>
It was time for him to feel me think<br>
and search for a better way.<br><br>
Shadows crept across the floor<br>
but the silence remained unbroken.<br>
Time had come to settle the score<br>
and these words were carefully spoken.<br><br>
&quot;You are special to me, my brother.<br>
I feel and have felt your pain.<br>
Remember that we need one another,<br>
if we're ever to come home again.<br><br>
Forgive those who laughed and spit,<br>
and honor the ones who died.<br>
You and I can scale this pit<br>
and lift ourselves with pride.&quot;<br><br>
Yes, we shed for them our blood and tears<br>
and gave away our precious youth.<br>
But history is cleansed, by the passing years.<br>
Now, some have realized the shameful truth.<br><br>
Let us receive what praise they choose to give.<br>
Rise up, tall and proud, and stand close to me.<br>
We fought hard that they might live<br>
and share a nation that is strong and free.<br><br>
Our Father longs to reward us well.<br>
He will replace what the locust hath eaten.<br>
We can tell the devil to go straight to hell...<br>
He knows for sure, `We were never beaten!&quot;<br><br>
From &quot;Scars and Stripes, Forever&quot; Copyright 1990 by Edward Ramon<br><br>
Thanks Brothers, for jerking my chain.  I'll get over it some day.   <br><br>

